Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which supports the euro by setting constraints on the size of budget deficits of EU members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavy weight of the Union, has not succeeded in keeping its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Moreover, it has used its political weight to cover the warning signal of its deficit, set up by the European Commission according to the terms of the Stability Pact.
Today it is France that is playing the bad boy.
The second largest member of the Union, not very enthusiastic, has officially stated it cannot meet its commitment to reduce the budget deficit one year after a formal warning was issued to tiny Ireland regarding its fiscal policies despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the Stability Pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems very affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it, as well as those aimed at amending it.
And rightly so: the Pact is poorly designed and its implementation is poorly done.
Limited to 3% of GDP, the deficit limit is arbitrary without consideration of the fact that deficits increase automatically when the economy slows down.
Admitting this fact, the architects of the pact exacerbated the situation by adopting two "poorly thought-out" solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is almost impossible in practice.
Fearing that serious slowdowns could breach the ceiling on deficits, they declared that a normal deficit was equivalent to no deficit at all.
Thus, every year, each country must submit a budget forecast for the next two years demonstrating how budgetary equilibrium will be achieved at some point.
Germany's commitment for 2002 was taken in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The minister of finance, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal austerity policy.
The Commission, seeking to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation in France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, especially regarding tax relief.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it is not just a matter of political acumen, but also economic savvy, as budgetary expenditures must be minimized.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain financial privileges paid for by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitively poorly perceived.
Therefore, France cannot meet its targets, and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has become adept at defying the laws of the Union.
Political maneuvers will inevitably follow.
Economists and cynics are not particularly surprised.
The aim of the pact—to establish fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency—is entirely reasonable.
However, with the loss of control over their national monetary policy, members of the Union have only one macroeconomic tool left: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The Stability Pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set up by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
A solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we do not have to look far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy has truly been successful.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it just requires delegating this policy to a competent group, the central bank, and giving it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any misstep will need to be addressed in the future, it is up to them to exercise good judgment.
This has turned out to be one of the major improvements in the monetary domain in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Naturally, some fear losing democracy in the process.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy fulfills two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure both in terms of expenditures and revenues.
The decisions concerning these issues cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and subject to parliamentary approval and management
The second is macroeconomic: it is about defining the budgetary balance to manage fluctuations in economic cycles.
This differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, the task for Europe is clear.
Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its deficit or surplus decisions, to an Independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is to stabilize (or reduce, for some countries) public debt.
Pour en garantir le résultat, le statut d'un tel Comité et ses mandats doivent faire l'objet d'un consensus au sein de l'Union, sans aucune interférence de Bruxelles, sans aucun règlement arbitraire, sans aucune prise de décision politique, mais tout simplement en se fiant au bon sens commun.
